[[File:Henry of Lancaster's cross, C.W. Mason.jpg|thumb|Cross erected commemorating [[Henry IV of England|Henry IV]]'s landing at Ravenspurn; the cross was later removed to Holyrood House in [[Hedon]]]]
'''Ravenspurn''' was a town in the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], England, which was lost due to [[coastal erosion]], one of more than 30 along the [[Holderness]] Coast which have been lost to the [[North Sea]] since the 19th century. The town was located close to the end of a peninsula near [[Ravenser Odd]], which has also been flooded.  The peninsula still survives and is known as [[Spurn|Spurn Head]].  The North Sea lies to the east of the peninsula, the river [[Humber]] to the west.

The nearest major city was [[Kingston upon Hull]].

The region of coastline is known as the Holderness Coast; geologically the land is formed of [[Till|glacial till]]s ([[boulder clay]]), which are subject to coastal erosion. Now at sea, areas around the site are being drilled for [[natural gas]].

Ravenspurn appears in [[William Shakespeare]]'s plays ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'', ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]]'', and ''[[Henry VI, Part 3]]'', under the spelling "Ravenspurgh".

Two medieval English kings landed at Ravenspurn: [[Henry IV of England|Henry IV]] in 1399, on his way to dethrone [[Richard II of England|Richard II]], and [[Edward IV of England|Edward IV]] in 1471, on his way back from exile in the [[Netherlands]], where he was resisted by the local lord, Sir Martin de la See.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.spurnhead.co.uk/ravenspurn.html | title=Spurn Head - East Riding of Yorkshire | publisher=spurnhead.co.uk | accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref>

